WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.107
Deep Dive: Know Your City — A Guide to Jefferson

00:00:04.107 --> 00:00:08.215
City and Cole County Local Government. Welcome to a deep

00:00:08.215 --> 00:00:12.322
dive episode. Today we're doing something a little different. Instead

00:00:12.322 --> 00:00:16.430
of covering the daily news, we're building a foundation —

00:00:16.430 --> 00:00:20.537
a comprehensive guide to the local government, economy, and civic

00:00:20.537 --> 00:00:24.644
life of Jefferson City and Cole County, Missouri. If you

00:00:24.644 --> 00:00:28.752
live here and you've ever wondered who's actually making decisions

00:00:28.752 --> 00:00:32.859
about your roads, your water, your property taxes, and your

00:00:32.859 --> 00:00:36.966
schools — this episode is for you. And a quick

00:00:36.966 --> 00:00:41.074
note before we begin: Jefferson City is the state capital,

00:00:41.074 --> 00:00:45.181
which means a lot of news sounds local but is

00:00:45.181 --> 00:00:49.289
really about statewide politics. This episode is exclusively about local

00:00:49.289 --> 00:00:53.396
government — city council, county commission, school board, and the

00:00:53.396 --> 00:00:57.503
people and projects that directly affect daily life in Jeff

00:00:57.503 --> 00:01:01.611
City. Let's start with the big picture. Chapter one. The

00:01:01.611 --> 00:01:05.718
City at a Glance. Jefferson City has a population of

00:01:05.718 --> 00:01:09.826
roughly forty-two thousand five hundred people. Cole County as a

00:01:09.826 --> 00:01:13.933
whole is about seventy-seven thousand three hundred. The broader metro

00:01:13.933 --> 00:01:18.040
area, which includes Callaway, Moniteau, and Osage counties, is around

00:01:18.040 --> 00:01:22.148
a hundred and fifty thousand. Here's the thing that might

00:01:22.148 --> 00:01:26.255
surprise you: the city isn't really growing. Population has been

00:01:26.255 --> 00:01:30.363
essentially flat, actually declining slightly from about forty-three thousand two

00:01:30.363 --> 00:01:34.470
hundred in the twenty-twenty census to around forty-two thousand five

00:01:34.470 --> 00:01:38.577
hundred today. Cole County grew about eight percent over the

00:01:38.577 --> 00:01:42.685
twenty years between two thousand and twenty-twenty, but that growth

00:01:42.685 --> 00:01:46.792
has stalled in recent years. The mayor has set a

00:01:46.792 --> 00:01:50.899
goal of reaching fifty thousand residents. Getting there would require

00:01:50.899 --> 00:01:55.007
three to five thousand new housing units over the next

00:01:55.007 --> 00:01:59.114
decade. And housing, as we'll discuss later, is one of

00:01:59.114 --> 00:02:03.222
the city's biggest challenges. The economy here is dominated by

00:02:03.222 --> 00:02:07.329
state government. Twenty-eight thousand government jobs exist in Jefferson City,

00:02:07.329 --> 00:02:11.436
with roughly seventeen thousand of those in Missouri state government.

00:02:11.436 --> 00:02:15.544
That makes the state by far the largest employer. Beyond

00:02:15.544 --> 00:02:19.651
that, the economy includes banking — Central Bancompany and Hawthorn

00:02:19.651 --> 00:02:23.759
Bancshares are both headquartered here — healthcare through Capital Region

00:02:23.759 --> 00:02:27.866
Medical Center, and manufacturing with companies like Unilever and Hitachi

00:02:27.866 --> 00:02:31.973
Energy. The cost of living is genuinely low. Overall, it's

00:02:31.973 --> 00:02:36.081
about seven percent below the national average. Housing is twenty-two

00:02:36.081 --> 00:02:40.188
percent below average, with a median home sale price around

00:02:40.188 --> 00:02:44.295
two hundred and thirty thousand dollars. Average rent is just

00:02:44.295 --> 00:02:48.403
five hundred and sixty-three dollars a month, which is sixty-four

00:02:48.403 --> 00:02:52.510
percent below the national average. Those are striking numbers. Chapter

00:02:52.510 --> 00:02:56.618
two. How the City Government Works. Jefferson City operates under

00:02:56.618 --> 00:03:00.725
a mayor-council form of government with a city administrator who

00:03:00.725 --> 00:03:04.832
handles day-to-day operations. The mayor is Ron L. Fitzwater. He's

00:03:04.832 --> 00:03:08.940
nonpartisan, took office on April seventeenth, twenty twenty-three, and his

00:03:08.940 --> 00:03:13.047
term runs through twenty twenty-seven. As chief executive, Fitzwater proposes

00:03:13.047 --> 00:03:17.155
the budget, signs legislation, appoints department directors and board members,

00:03:17.155 --> 00:03:21.262
and casts tie-breaking votes on the city council. You can

00:03:21.262 --> 00:03:25.369
reach his office at five-seven-three, six-three-four, six-three-oh-three. The city administrator

00:03:25.369 --> 00:03:29.477
is Brian Crane. He's a Jefferson City native, a Helias

00:03:29.477 --> 00:03:33.584
Catholic grad, with nineteen-plus years in municipal management including stints

00:03:33.584 --> 00:03:37.691
in Moberly and Holts Summit. Crane has a bachelor's in

00:03:37.691 --> 00:03:41.799
political science from Lincoln University and an M-B-A from William

00:03:41.799 --> 00:03:45.906
Woods. He's an I-C-M-A credentialed manager. His job is to

00:03:45.906 --> 00:03:50.014
run the machinery of city government — administering all city

00:03:50.014 --> 00:03:54.121
affairs, coordinating departments, and managing most city employees. Now, the

00:03:54.121 --> 00:03:58.228
city council. This is where most of the legislative action

00:03:58.228 --> 00:04:02.336
happens. The council has ten members — two per ward

00:04:02.336 --> 00:04:06.443
across five wards — serving staggered two-year terms. There's a

00:04:06.443 --> 00:04:10.551
term limit of four consecutive terms, after which you have

00:04:10.551 --> 00:04:14.658
to sit out one election cycle. Here's the current lineup.

00:04:14.658 --> 00:04:18.765
In Ward One, Randy Hoselton, whose term expires in twenty

00:04:18.765 --> 00:04:22.873
twenty-six, and Jeff Ahlers, expiring twenty twenty-seven. Ward Two has

00:04:22.873 --> 00:04:26.980
Mike Lester, expiring twenty twenty-six, and one vacant seat for

00:04:26.980 --> 00:04:31.088
the twenty twenty-seven term. Ward Three is Treaka Young, twenty

00:04:31.088 --> 00:04:35.195
twenty-six, and Derek Thomas, twenty twenty-seven. Ward Four has Chris

00:04:35.195 --> 00:04:39.302
Leuckel, twenty twenty-six, and Julie Allen, twenty twenty-seven. And Ward

00:04:39.302 --> 00:04:43.410
Five is Mackenzie Job, twenty twenty-six, and Shane Kampeter, twenty

00:04:43.410 --> 00:04:47.517
twenty-seven. Five seats — one per ward — expire this

00:04:47.517 --> 00:04:51.624
year, which means the April twenty twenty-six elections could meaningfully

00:04:51.624 --> 00:04:55.732
reshape the council. The council meets on the first and

00:04:55.732 --> 00:04:59.839
third Monday of each month. Pre-meeting discussion starts at five

00:04:59.839 --> 00:05:03.947
forty-five P-M, and the official meeting begins at six P-M.

00:05:03.947 --> 00:05:08.054
Everything happens at the John G. Christy Municipal Building at

00:05:08.054 --> 00:05:12.161
three-twenty East McCarty Street. Meetings are open to the public,

00:05:12.161 --> 00:05:16.269
and video recordings are posted online at the city website,

00:05:16.269 --> 00:05:20.376
jefferson city M-O dot gov. The city's approved budget for

00:05:20.376 --> 00:05:24.484
the current year is eighty-six point eight million dollars. Key

00:05:24.484 --> 00:05:28.591
city departments include police, fire, public works, streets, transit —

00:05:28.591 --> 00:05:32.698
that's Jeff Tran — wastewater, parks and recreation, planning and

00:05:32.698 --> 00:05:36.806
zoning, and the city clerk's office. Chapter three. How Cole

00:05:36.806 --> 00:05:40.913
County Government Works. Cole County operates under a three-member county

00:05:40.913 --> 00:05:45.020
commission, which is standard under Missouri law. The presiding commissioner

00:05:45.020 --> 00:05:49.128
is Sam Bushman, who serves the entire county. The eastern

00:05:49.128 --> 00:05:53.235
district commissioner is Jeff Hoelscher, and the western district commissioner

00:05:53.235 --> 00:05:57.343
is Harry Otto. The commission meets on Tuesdays at nine

00:05:57.343 --> 00:06:01.450
A-M at three-eleven East High Street. Meeting agendas and video

00:06:01.450 --> 00:06:05.557
recordings are available through the county website at cole county

00:06:05.557 --> 00:06:09.665
dot org. Beyond the commission, there are ten elected county

00:06:09.665 --> 00:06:13.772
officials you should know about. Tim Theroff is the county

00:06:13.772 --> 00:06:17.880
assessor — and he's new, having taken over in September

00:06:17.880 --> 00:06:21.987
twenty twenty-five, which we'll get into. Jay Moore is the

00:06:21.987 --> 00:06:26.094
county auditor. Mark Eichholz is the circuit clerk. Larry Vincent

00:06:26.094 --> 00:06:30.202
is the collector of revenue. Steve Korsmeyer is the county

00:06:30.202 --> 00:06:34.309
clerk, who also handles election supervision and voter registration. Locke

00:06:34.309 --> 00:06:38.416
Thompson is the prosecuting attorney. Ralph Jobe is the public

00:06:38.416 --> 00:06:42.524
administrator. Judy Ridgeway is the recorder of deeds. John P.

00:06:42.524 --> 00:06:46.631
Wheeler is the sheriff. And Eric Peters is the treasurer.

00:06:46.631 --> 00:06:50.739
The county runs eighteen departments covering everything from E-M-S —

00:06:50.739 --> 00:06:54.846
which responds to over ten thousand calls per year —

00:06:54.846 --> 00:06:58.953
to the health department, public works, GIS mapping, and emergency

00:06:58.953 --> 00:07:03.061
management. Financially, the county's twenty twenty-six operating budget is sixty-four

00:07:03.061 --> 00:07:07.168
point four million dollars, with operating expenses of sixty point

00:07:07.168 --> 00:07:11.276
one million, leaving a modest surplus of four point three

00:07:11.276 --> 00:07:15.383
million. On top of that, thirty-two point eight million was

00:07:15.383 --> 00:07:19.490
approved for capital improvements. The county had fifty-six point four

00:07:19.490 --> 00:07:23.598
million in reserves at the end of twenty twenty-five. But

00:07:23.598 --> 00:07:27.705
the financial picture isn't entirely rosy. Capital improvement sales tax

00:07:27.705 --> 00:07:31.813
revenue underperformed — the county projected two percent growth but

00:07:31.813 --> 00:07:35.920
only saw zero point six percent. COVID stimulus funds have

00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:40.027
been fully depleted. County Auditor Jay Moore has warned that

00:07:40.027 --> 00:07:44.135
revenues are, quote, getting tighter, and the county needs to

00:07:44.135 --> 00:07:48.242
watch spending carefully in twenty twenty-six. Chapter four. Jefferson City

00:07:48.242 --> 00:07:52.349
Public Schools. The school district serves about eight thousand five

00:07:52.349 --> 00:07:56.457
hundred sixty students across eighteen schools: one early childhood center,

00:07:56.457 --> 00:08:00.564
eleven elementary schools, two middle schools, two high schools —

00:08:00.564 --> 00:08:04.672
Jefferson City High School and Capital City High School —

00:08:04.672 --> 00:08:08.779
one alternative school, and Nichols Career Center. The district covers

00:08:08.779 --> 00:08:12.886
two hundred twenty-three square miles across both Cole and Callaway

00:08:12.886 --> 00:08:16.994
counties. Student demographics are about sixty-one percent white, twenty percent

00:08:16.994 --> 00:08:21.101
African American, seven percent Hispanic, two percent Asian, and ten

00:08:21.101 --> 00:08:25.209
percent multiracial. Per-student spending is twelve thousand one hundred eighty-two

00:08:25.209 --> 00:08:29.316
dollars annually. The school board has seven elected volunteer members

00:08:29.316 --> 00:08:33.423
serving three-year terms. Anne Bloemke-Warren is president, Ken Hussey is

00:08:33.423 --> 00:08:37.531
vice president, and Brad Bates is treasurer. The board meets

00:08:37.531 --> 00:08:41.638
monthly at the JCPS Education Offices on Dix Road. Academically,

00:08:41.638 --> 00:08:45.745
the district has been on an encouraging trajectory. Composite scores

00:08:45.745 --> 00:08:49.853
have improved for three consecutive years — from seventy-one percent

00:08:49.853 --> 00:08:53.960
in twenty twenty-two to seventy-seven percent in twenty twenty-three to

00:08:53.960 --> 00:08:58.068
eighty-four percent in twenty twenty-four. The latest figure is eighty-three

00:08:58.068 --> 00:09:02.175
point two percent. Jefferson City High School is ranked number

00:09:02.175 --> 00:09:06.282
one in the metro area and number fifty-eight statewide. On

00:09:06.282 --> 00:09:10.390
the capital side, the district has been busy. A twenty

00:09:10.390 --> 00:09:14.497
seventeen bond issue, Prop J, funded Capital City High School,

00:09:14.497 --> 00:09:18.605
which opened in fall twenty nineteen, and renovated Jefferson City

00:09:18.605 --> 00:09:22.712
High School. An eighty-five million dollar bond in April twenty

00:09:22.712 --> 00:09:26.819
twenty-two is funding a new early childhood center, technology upgrades

00:09:26.819 --> 00:09:30.927
across all schools, and renovations at both middle schools. And

00:09:30.927 --> 00:09:35.034
right now, a twenty million dollar athletic facilities expansion is

00:09:35.034 --> 00:09:39.141
underway — tennis complex, baseball, softball, and soccer fields —

00:09:39.141 --> 00:09:43.249
expected to run from spring twenty twenty-six through summer twenty

00:09:43.249 --> 00:09:47.356
twenty-seven. Three school board seats expire in twenty twenty-six, so

00:09:47.356 --> 00:09:51.464
those elections are also coming up. Chapter five. The Big

00:09:51.464 --> 00:09:55.571
Issues. Let's talk about the persistent challenges that have shaped

00:09:55.571 --> 00:09:59.678
this community over the last decade. First, the twenty nineteen

00:09:59.678 --> 00:10:03.786
tornado. On May twenty-second, twenty nineteen, an E-F-three tornado with

00:10:03.786 --> 00:10:07.893
one hundred sixty mile per hour winds cut a thirty-two

00:10:07.893 --> 00:10:12.001
mile path through central Missouri and directly through Jefferson City.

00:10:12.001 --> 00:10:16.108
Five hundred sixteen homes were damaged. Eighty government buildings were

00:10:16.108 --> 00:10:20.215
hit. Eighty-two businesses were affected. Insurance claims totaled one hundred

00:10:20.215 --> 00:10:24.323
seventy million dollars. About a hundred and fifty housing units

00:10:24.323 --> 00:10:28.430
were destroyed. Thirty-three people were injured, though remarkably, no one

00:10:28.430 --> 00:10:32.538
was killed. At the five-year anniversary in twenty twenty-four, rebuilding

00:10:32.538 --> 00:10:36.645
was still underway. Twelve buildings still needed to be torn

00:10:36.645 --> 00:10:40.752
down two years after the storm. The tornado's damage to

00:10:40.752 --> 00:10:44.860
the housing stock is still felt today — it worsened

00:10:44.860 --> 00:10:48.967
what was already a tight market and fundamentally reshaped development

00:10:48.967 --> 00:10:53.074
patterns in parts of the city. Which brings us to

00:10:53.074 --> 00:10:57.182
the housing crisis. A twenty twenty-two needs assessment officially declared

00:10:57.182 --> 00:11:01.289
Jefferson City in a housing crisis. After the tornado, the

00:11:01.289 --> 00:11:05.397
city was ranked the twelfth tightest housing market in the

00:11:05.397 --> 00:11:09.504
nation by the National Association of Realtors. The most acute

00:11:09.504 --> 00:11:13.611
shortage is in affordable rental housing. The city has responded

00:11:13.611 --> 00:11:17.719
with a developer incentive program offering five thousand dollars per

00:11:17.719 --> 00:11:21.826
new unit, and the C-M-C-A is building a forty-unit affordable

00:11:21.826 --> 00:11:25.934
apartment complex called Stronghold Landing, expected to open in summer

00:11:25.934 --> 00:11:30.041
twenty twenty-six. But the gap between supply and demand remains

00:11:30.041 --> 00:11:34.148
enormous. Then there's infrastructure. The High Street Viaduct is the

00:11:34.148 --> 00:11:38.256
current poster child for this problem. Built in nineteen forty-nine,

00:11:38.256 --> 00:11:42.363
it was emergency-closed in February twenty twenty-six after structural deterioration

00:11:42.363 --> 00:11:46.470
was discovered — a large hole with deteriorated concrete and

00:11:46.470 --> 00:11:50.578
steel. A temporary repair costing about thirty-four thousand dollars is

00:11:50.578 --> 00:11:54.685
being done to reopen it, but the long-term replacement is

00:11:54.685 --> 00:11:58.793
estimated at sixteen to eighteen million dollars, potentially up to

00:11:58.793 --> 00:12:02.900
twenty-five million if a second bridge to Deborah Cooper Park

00:12:02.900 --> 00:12:07.007
is included. The city has applied for a federal BUILD

00:12:07.007 --> 00:12:11.115
grant of up to twenty-five million. The county commission voted

00:12:11.115 --> 00:12:15.222
to support that application. But the viaduct is just one

00:12:15.222 --> 00:12:19.330
example. Aging water and sewer systems, roads, and bridges across

00:12:19.330 --> 00:12:23.437
the city and county all need significant investment. Water rates

00:12:23.437 --> 00:12:27.544
are increasing four point seven five percent annually through twenty

00:12:27.544 --> 00:12:31.652
twenty-nine just to maintain the system. Flooding is another recurring

00:12:31.652 --> 00:12:35.759
concern. The Great Flood of nineteen ninety-three set the benchmark

00:12:35.759 --> 00:12:39.866
— the Missouri River stayed above flood stage for sixty-two

00:12:39.866 --> 00:12:43.974
days and crested at thirty-eight point six feet. The twenty

00:12:43.974 --> 00:12:48.081
nineteen flood reached thirty-three point four feet. The Capital View

00:12:48.081 --> 00:12:52.189
levee and ongoing flood management remain critical infrastructure. Crime has

00:12:52.189 --> 00:12:56.296
also been a persistent issue. The city's crime rate runs

00:12:56.296 --> 00:13:00.403
at twenty-four per one thousand residents, which is above the

00:13:00.403 --> 00:13:04.511
national average. There's significant geographic variation — southwest neighborhoods are

00:13:04.511 --> 00:13:08.618
the safest, while northeast neighborhoods have the highest rates. Violent

00:13:08.618 --> 00:13:12.726
crime increased twenty-two percent in recent reporting. The city council

00:13:12.726 --> 00:13:16.833
is examining the quarter-cent public safety sales tax as budget

00:13:16.833 --> 00:13:20.940
pressures mount. And finally, the property tax assessment debacle. In

00:13:20.940 --> 00:13:25.048
twenty twenty-five, Cole County Assessor Chris Estes received a failing

00:13:25.048 --> 00:13:29.155
grade from the Missouri State Tax Commission. He hadn't completed

00:13:29.155 --> 00:13:33.263
the required countywide reassessment every two years, citing staff shortages

00:13:33.263 --> 00:13:37.370
and software problems. His workaround — assessing half the county

00:13:37.370 --> 00:13:41.477
in twenty twenty-three and the other half in twenty twenty-five

00:13:41.477 --> 00:13:45.585
— was non-compliant and created deeply inequitable tax increases: thirteen

00:13:45.585 --> 00:13:49.692
percent for some homeowners, six to seven percent for others.

00:13:49.692 --> 00:13:53.799
Estes retired at the end of August twenty twenty-five, and

00:13:53.799 --> 00:13:57.907
Tim Theroff took over on September first. The county is

00:13:57.907 --> 00:14:02.014
still working toward compliance, and the equity concerns haven't been

00:14:02.014 --> 00:14:06.122
fully resolved. Chapter six. Policy Shifts and What's Changing. A

00:14:06.122 --> 00:14:10.229
few significant policy shifts are worth understanding. The capital improvement

00:14:10.229 --> 00:14:14.336
sales tax, originally approved in nineteen eighty-six, has been renewed

00:14:14.336 --> 00:14:18.444
every five years. Eighty-five percent goes to roads and bridges,

00:14:18.444 --> 00:14:22.551
fifteen percent to county capital improvements. In January twenty twenty-six,

00:14:22.551 --> 00:14:26.659
commissioners approved a resolution to change the next renewal from

00:14:26.659 --> 00:14:30.766
five years to ten. The logic is that grant timelines

00:14:30.766 --> 00:14:34.873
have lengthened and infrastructure projects need longer planning horizons. This

00:14:34.873 --> 00:14:38.981
goes to voters in April twenty twenty-six. If it fails,

00:14:38.981 --> 00:14:43.088
the county loses its primary funding mechanism for road and

00:14:43.088 --> 00:14:47.195
bridge work. The city has launched housing incentive programs that

00:14:47.195 --> 00:14:51.303
didn't exist before — the five-thousand-dollar per unit developer reimbursement

00:14:51.303 --> 00:14:55.410
represents a shift toward actively subsidizing new construction. And the

00:14:55.410 --> 00:14:59.518
downtown revitalization push marks a deliberate strategic pivot. Jefferson Matters

00:14:59.518 --> 00:15:03.625
won the twenty twenty-five Great American Main Street Award. The

00:15:03.625 --> 00:15:07.732
conference center and hotel project was approved. The River Market

00:15:07.732 --> 00:15:11.840
is under construction. These represent a conscious decision to invest

00:15:11.840 --> 00:15:15.947
in downtown as an economic engine rather than continuing to

00:15:15.947 --> 00:15:20.055
let development sprawl outward. Chapter seven. The Big Projects Coming.

00:15:20.055 --> 00:15:24.162
Looking ahead at the next five to seven years, here's

00:15:24.162 --> 00:15:28.269
what's in the pipeline. The downtown conference center is probably

00:15:28.269 --> 00:15:32.377
the biggest economic bet the city has made in years.

00:15:32.377 --> 00:15:36.484
It's a hundred eighty-nine thousand four hundred twenty square feet

00:15:36.484 --> 00:15:40.591
of mixed-use space including a conference center, a two hundred

00:15:40.591 --> 00:15:44.699
room full-service hotel, a grand ballroom, restaurant, coffee shop, and

00:15:44.699 --> 00:15:48.806
five hundred twenty-six parking spaces. It's located between Madison and

00:15:48.806 --> 00:15:52.914
Monroe streets on East Capitol Avenue. The projected economic impact

00:15:52.914 --> 00:15:57.021
is five hundred eighty-four million dollars over a decade, supporting

00:15:57.021 --> 00:16:01.128
three hundred seventy-two jobs and generating fourteen million in local

00:16:01.128 --> 00:16:05.236
tax revenue. Construction starts in twenty twenty-six with completion expected

00:16:05.236 --> 00:16:09.343
around twenty twenty-eight. The River Market project is transforming the

00:16:09.343 --> 00:16:13.451
historic riverfront near the Missouri State Penitentiary site into a

00:16:13.451 --> 00:16:17.558
community gathering space. Summer twenty twenty-six is the target completion.

00:16:17.558 --> 00:16:21.665
The Jefferson City Memorial Airport is getting a new control

00:16:21.665 --> 00:16:25.773
tower — an eight point seven million dollar project funded

00:16:25.773 --> 00:16:29.880
through congressional appropriations, F-A-A grants, and city and state contributions.

00:16:29.880 --> 00:16:33.988
It should be done by late fall twenty twenty-six. The

00:16:33.988 --> 00:16:38.095
Capital Area Rail Terminal, or CART, is a multimodal transload

00:16:38.095 --> 00:16:42.202
facility in Algoa Industrial Park, funded by two point two

00:16:42.202 --> 00:16:46.310
million in state and federal grants. It's an industrial rail

00:16:46.310 --> 00:16:50.417
spur extension that could open new economic development possibilities. Cole

00:16:50.417 --> 00:16:54.524
County's five-year capital program includes roughly fifty projects with an

00:16:54.524 --> 00:16:58.632
estimated ninety million dollar investment in roads, bridges, traffic, and

00:16:58.632 --> 00:17:02.739
street infrastructure. And the Missouri State Penitentiary redevelopment remains a

00:17:02.739 --> 00:17:06.847
long-term opportunity — twenty-three acres of strategically located land blending

00:17:06.847 --> 00:17:10.954
historical preservation with modern development. Chapter eight. How to Stay

00:17:10.954 --> 00:17:15.061
Informed. So how do you actually keep up with all

00:17:15.061 --> 00:17:19.169
of this? City council meetings happen on the first and

00:17:19.169 --> 00:17:23.276
third Mondays at six P-M. You can attend in person

00:17:23.276 --> 00:17:27.384
at the Christy Municipal Building on McCarty Street, or watch

00:17:27.384 --> 00:17:31.491
the video recordings posted on the city's website. Agendas are

00:17:31.491 --> 00:17:35.598
published in advance. County commission meetings are every Tuesday at

00:17:35.598 --> 00:17:39.706
nine A-M. The county posts agendas and meeting videos through

00:17:39.706 --> 00:17:43.813
its agenda center at cole county dot org. The school

00:17:43.813 --> 00:17:47.920
board meets monthly. Documents are available through Board Docs on

00:17:47.920 --> 00:17:52.028
the JCPS website. For news coverage, the Jefferson City News

00:17:52.028 --> 00:17:56.135
Tribune is the most consistent source for local government reporting.

00:17:56.135 --> 00:18:00.243
A-B-C seventeen and K-R-C-G also cover major local stories. The

00:18:00.243 --> 00:18:04.350
key is filtering for genuinely local coverage versus state politics

00:18:04.350 --> 00:18:08.457
stories that just happen to have a Jefferson City dateline.

00:18:08.457 --> 00:18:12.565
You can sign up for city alerts through the official

00:18:12.565 --> 00:18:16.672
website and for county notifications through the Notify Me system

00:18:16.672 --> 00:18:20.780
on cole county dot org. And pay attention to what's

00:18:20.780 --> 00:18:24.887
coming up. The April twenty twenty-six election is consequential. Five

00:18:24.887 --> 00:18:28.994
city council seats, three school board seats, and the county

00:18:28.994 --> 00:18:33.102
capital improvement sales tax renewal are all on the ballot.

00:18:33.102 --> 00:18:37.209
These decisions will shape how the city and county operate

00:18:37.209 --> 00:18:41.316
for years. Chapter nine. The Interconnected Picture. Here's what makes

00:18:41.316 --> 00:18:45.424
all of this interesting when you step back. These issues

00:18:45.424 --> 00:18:49.531
aren't independent — they compound and interact. The tornado destroyed

00:18:49.531 --> 00:18:53.639
housing, which deepened a housing crisis, which drove up rents,

00:18:53.639 --> 00:18:57.746
which worsened affordability. Aging infrastructure led to deferred maintenance, which

00:18:57.746 --> 00:19:01.853
led to emergency repairs like the viaduct, which created budget

00:19:01.853 --> 00:19:05.961
pressure. COVID stimulus funds papered over revenue shortfalls for a

00:19:05.961 --> 00:19:10.068
few years, but now they're gone and revenues are tighter

00:19:10.068 --> 00:19:14.176
than projected. The property assessment failure created inequitable tax burdens,

00:19:14.176 --> 00:19:18.283
which erodes public trust, which makes it harder to pass

00:19:18.283 --> 00:19:22.390
tax renewals. And the downtown investment in the conference center

00:19:22.390 --> 00:19:26.498
and river market could generate real revenue — but that

00:19:26.498 --> 00:19:30.605
depends on solving the housing shortage and infrastructure backlog first.

00:19:30.605 --> 00:19:34.713
Understanding these dynamics is what makes the difference between passively

00:19:34.713 --> 00:19:38.820
hearing the news and actually understanding what's happening in the

00:19:38.820 --> 00:19:42.927
place where you live. That's our deep dive for today.

00:19:42.927 --> 00:19:47.035
This project is going to be ongoing — we've set

00:19:47.035 --> 00:19:51.142
up a weekly monitoring system that checks city council agendas,

00:19:51.142 --> 00:19:55.249
county commission actions, school board news, and local reporting every

00:19:55.249 --> 00:19:59.357
Monday. So as things develop, we'll be tracking them. Thanks

00:19:59.357 --> 00:20:02.232
for listening. This is Jacob's Daily Briefing.
